Author-Name: Bruno Biais 
Author-Name: Thomas Mariotti 
Author-Name: Jean-Charles Rochet 
Author-Name: St»phane Villeneuve 
Title: Large Risks, Limited Liability, and Dynamic Moral Hazard 
Abstract:
				 We study a continuous-time principal-agent
 model in which a risk-neutral agent with limited liability must exert
 unobservable effort to reduce the likelihood of large but relatively
 infrequent losses. Firm size can be decreased at no cost or increased
 subject to adjustment costs. In the optimal contract, investment takes
 place only if a long enough period of time elapses with no losses
 occurring. Then, if good performance continues, the agent is paid. As soon
 as a loss occurs, payments to the agent are suspended, and so is
 investment if further losses occur. Accumulated bad performance leads to
 downsizing. We derive explicit formulae for the dynamics of firm size and
 its asymptotic growth rate, and we provide conditions under which firm
 size eventually goes to zero or grows without bounds. Copyright  2010 The Econometric Society. 
